<!------------------------------------------- section ------------------------------------------------->
<div id="section">
  <h1><em>Saurabh Paul</em></h1>
  <p>
    I am a PhD student at the <a href="http://umdphysics.umd.edu/">Dept. of Physics</a>, <a href="http://jqi.umd.edu//">Joint Quantum Institute</a> and <a href="http://quics.umd.edu/">Joint Center for Quantum Information and Computer Science</a>, University of Maryland, College Park. I work in the 
    <a href="http://jqi.umd.edu/research-group/tiesinga">group</a> 
    of Dr. Eite Tiesinga. I did my Masters in Physics from the 
    <a href="http://www.iitk.ac.in/">Indian Institute of Technology, Kanpur</a>, India and my Bachelor of Science, Physics (Hons) from 
    <a href="http://www.bhu.ac.in/">Banaras Hindu University</a>, India.
  </p>

  <p>
    My 
    <a href="research.html">research</a> 
    involves theoretically studying many-body quantum systems engineered using <a href="http://groups.jqi.umd.edu/porto/research/cold-atoms-optical-lattices">ultra-cold atoms in optical lattices</a>. This has burgeoned into a highly exciting research area, and has become the testing ground for a huge array of condensed matter and quantum phenomena. In my research, I do analytical as well as extensive numerical computations. Initially, much of the coding I did was in Fortran 90. In the last couple of years, I have switched to a large extent to using Python. I am proficient in Mathematica and also familiar with C++. I use <a href="http://www.ubuntu.com/">Ubuntu</a> most of the time, with intermittent use of 
    <a href="https://access.redhat.com/products/red-hat-enterprise-linux/">Red Hat Enterprise Linux</a> 
    in my office desktop. As an aside, I also have some familiarity with HTML and CSS, a knowledge that came handy in creating this webpage!
  </p>

  <p>
    I love photography! It gives me immense joy and also acts as a stress buster. You would usually find me photo editing in my pastime! Also, I am a big foodie and enjoy cooking a ton!
  </p>
  
</div>
